# The shadowing problem
    When you’re learning object-oriented programming in Java, one thing that often causes confusion is the shadowing problem.
    This happens when a local variable (like a parameter in a method or constructor) has the same name as an instance variable of the class.

    It may not cause any errors, but it can break your program in a sneaky way — making it hard to spot the issue. Let’s understand this with a simple example.

Q1. What Is Variable Shadowing? 🤔

    Variable shadowing happens when a variable declared inside a method or constructor has the same name as a variable defined in the class.

    In such a case, Java gives priority to the local variable, which means the class-level (instance) variable is hidden or “shadowed.”

    So if you try to set a value inside the constructor using the same name, it won’t actually change the class variable — it just updates the local one.

# Key Takeaways:
    1. Variable shadowing happens when a local variable (like a method or constructor parameter) has the same name as an instance variable in the class.
    2. In such cases, Java uses the local variable instead of the instance variable — so the actual class variable is ignored or “shadowed.”
    3. Shadowing does not give an error, but your object might not behave as expected because the real variable doesn’t get the right value.
    4. This is a common mistake when writing constructors that assign values to instance variables.
    5. Always check for shadowing if your object values are showing null or not updating as expected.
    6. Shadowing is a logic-level problem, not a syntax-level problem — so it may go unnoticed until you see the wrong output.

# Common Interview Questions & Answers 💬

    Q1. What is variable shadowing in Java?
        Variable shadowing happens when a local variable (like a parameter in a method or constructor) has the same name as an instance variable.
        The local variable hides or “shadows” the instance variable within that scope.

    Q2. What is the result of variable shadowing in constructors?
        If you try to assign a value using variable = variable;, Java uses the local variable (parameter),
        so the assignment doesn't update the instance variable. The class variable remains unchanged (like null or 0), which causes incorrect behavior in the program.

    Q3. Does variable shadowing give a compile-time error?
        No, and that’s what makes it tricky. Java doesn’t show any error, but the code silently fails to do what you intended.
        The object is created with missing or wrong data.

    Q4. How do you fix variable shadowing?
        Use the this keyword to refer to the class-level (instance) variable. For example: this.color = color;
        clearly tells Java to assign the parameter to the instance variable.

    Q5. Can shadowing happen outside constructors?
        Yes. Shadowing can happen in any method or block where a local variable or parameter has the same name as a class or global variable.

