    2. It helps solve the shadowing problem, where a parameter name hides the instance variable
    3. this.variable = parameter; is the correct way to assign values when names are the same
    4. Without this, your object’s data might not get set properly
    5. It makes your code easier to read, write, and understand
    6. this is your way of telling Java: “Use the variable that belongs to this object”

# Common Interview Questions and Answers 💬

    Q1. What does the this keyword do in Java?
        It refers to the current object. It’s used to access instance variables and methods from within the class.

    Q2. Why do we use this in constructors?
        We use it when the constructor parameters have the same names as instance variables. It helps avoid confusion and assign the correct values.

    Q3. What happens if we don’t use this when names are the same?
        Java uses the local variable (parameter), and the instance variable stays unchanged. This leads to bugs like uninitialized variables (null values).

    Q4. Can we use this outside methods or constructors?
        No. this can only be used inside instance methods or constructors — not in static methods or outside the class.

    Q5. Is using this a must in all cases?
        No. It’s only needed when there’s a naming conflict. But using this is a good habit for clarity.


